<TEXT>
two masked men in overalls 
burst into a pub in east belfast on saturday shooting to death a 
protestant paramilitary leader and another man and wounding four 
others police said 
police identified one of the dead men as james craig 47 of 
belfast british television reports named him as a leader in the 
protestant paramilitary ulster defense association 
the second dead man was identified as belfast resident george 
raimey a spokesman for the royal ulster constabulary said 
raimeys age was unknown 
no group claimed responsibility for the attack but suspicion 
fell on the irish republican army which is fighting to end british 
rule in northern ireland the mainly roman catholic ira seeks to 
unite the predominantly protestant province with the neighboring 
irish republic 
police said the gunmen wearing blue overalls entered the 
castle inn in the heart of protestant east belfast and ordered the 
customers to lie on the floor 
the gunmen then opened fire indiscriminately and fled the 
police said adding that at least one of the wounded was in 
critical condition 
members of the ulster defense association have been accused of 
taking part in racketeering throughout the province 
craig and two other suspects appeared before belfast magistrates 
court in 1985 on 33 charges related to extortion of money from 
building contractors however the charges were later dropped 
in the last 10 months two leading members of the ulster defense 
association have been slain 
vice chairman john mcmichael was killed last christmas by a 
booby trap bomb attached to his car outside his home in lisburn 
county antrim william john quee was shot to death sept 7 outside 
his grocery store 
in the border area near the irish republic meanwhile police 
said a gun and grenade attack was launched on the royal ulster 
constabulary station at lurgan county armagh causing slight 
damage but no injuries there was no immediate claim of 
responsibility 
