<TEXT>
one in six britons questioned in a survey couldnt 
find his own country on a map and more than 40 percent had a big 
problem figuring a simple restaurant check a newspaper reported 
sunday 
one person even thought president reagan leads britains 
socialist labor party although 90 percent correctly identified the 
opposition leader as neil kinnock the survey found 
the survey of 994 people published in the sunday times of 
london was conducted last month by market and opinion research 
international the newspaper commissioned it to test knowledge of 
geography mathematics common foreign language phrases spelling 
history science and current affairs 
the newspaper said the 18question test was simple but 
many of the replies were enough to break traditional teachers 
hearts 
the survey found 83 percent of the sample population could find 
britain on a world map but 7 percent had no idea where to look 
others placed it off the coast of north america off south america 
in the far east or in africa 
asked to spell embarrass satellite and exercise 
one in 10 immediately threw up their hands in defeat the 
newspaper said 
fiftynine percent spelled embarrass and satellite 
incorrectly and 28 percent failed exercise 
mathematics added to the problem the newspaper said asked to 
add menu prices for the total cost of a hamburger french fries 
apple pie and coffee 42 percent got it wrong or were unable to try 
people aged 1524 fared the worst in the survey the newspaper 
said and women generally did worse than men except in spelling 
professor david hargreaves of cambridge university was quoted as 
saying the poor results by young people showed britain was in 
danger of producing a generation of ignoramuses 
education minister angela rumbold was quoted as describing the 
results as most depressing 
in july the gallup organization released results of a 
geographic literacy test that showed that the britons polled placed 
seventh among the nine countries surveyed americans tested 
finished sixth in the survey 
three out of four americans in the gallup survey couldnt locate 
the persian gulf most had no idea of the us population and the 
majority were lost when it came to finding britain france or japan 
