<TEXT>
vandals bombed and destroyed a statue 
of us gen douglas macarthur on an island where he led allied 
troops retaking the philippines from japan during world war ii 
police said sunday 
the 10foot statue of marble granite and cement fell to the 
ground face down most of it was blasted to pieces by the explosive 
device which police had not identified 
the bombing occurred before dawn saturday at palo town on the 
central island of leyte about 350 miles from manila the 
philippine daily inquirer reported that the blast was heard more 
than seven miles away 
the statue was one of six erected in 1976 on the shores of palo 
to commemorate the leyte landing but only macarthurs statue was 
damaged 
the bombing occurred five days before the 44th anniversary of 
the landing of allied forces he commanded their return fulfilled 
the famous pledge i shall return which macarthur made to 
filipinos when his troops fled japanese attackers at the beginning 
of the war 
no suspects were caught in the bombing and no motive was 
discovered 
however the island is a stronghold of communist rebels who have 
been fighting the national government for two decades 
</TEXT>
