<TEXT>
its been a downanddirty presidential 
campaign from gleeful democratic denunciations of george bush as a 
wimp to the republicans skewering of michael dukakis over crime 
the aclu and the pledge of allegiance 
while the dismal tenor of this years campaign discourse has 
elicited groans from past presidents richard nixon and jimmy 
carter political analysts credit bush with tapping some of the 
same emotional issues that helped nixon capture the white house in 
1968 and 1972 and laid the groundwork for ronald reagans twin 
landslides of the 1980s 
some experts say it is a serious mistake for the democrats who 
have lost four of the past five presidential elections to 
underestimate the seriousness with which the electorate responds to 
emotional appeals to its patriotism or fear of crime 
the gut issues symbolic or not are real issues for many voters 
politics is a matter of gut responses otherwise known as 
emotions said roger d masters a dartmouth university professor 
of government 
its not just media manipulation said michael robinson a 
georgetown university associate professor of government and expert 
on media and politics if the democrats continue to believe that 
symbolic issues dont matter theyre going to foul up time and 
time again 
stephen hess a senior fellow at the brookings institution said 
symbolic issues loom larger in this election because american 
politics like nature abhors a vacuum the candidates seemed quite 
deliberately to choose not to face up to the pragmatic issues 
robinson said the race unfolded during a time of economic 
prosperity when there were few differences between democrats and 
republicans on dealing with the soviet union 
when you subtract the issues of peace and prosperity you 
leave very little so we are left to fight on those gut isues of 
symbolic issues he said 
conservative analyst kevin phillips publisher of the american 
political report said the republicans have replayed the key 
cultural and patriotic issues with the swing voters that got the 
republican presidential majority started in 1968 and 1972 and 
1980 
the bush campaign flogged the crime spree of willie horton jr 
the massachusetts lifer who escaped while on a weekend furlough 
from prison and pummeled dukakis for being a selfproclaimed 
cardcarrying member of the american civil liberties union 
in doing so phillips said bushs people succeeded in 
rekindling in the minds of wavering reagan democrats the emotions 
that pulled them to vote for republican presidents in earlier 
years while dukakis failed to develop rival issues to appeal to 
the same swing voters 
in their final debate last thursday both candidates sounded 
apologetic about the lowroad campaigning bush recalling the 
almost nonstop attacks the democrats unleashed against him at 
their july convention in atlanta said i dont want to sound 
like a kid in the schoolyard but he started it 
it was both ways said ben wattenberg a senior fellow at 
the american enterprise institute two months ago the best issue 
that dukakis had on bush was wimp and the best issue bush had on 
dukakis was lword liberal 
the republicans went after dukakis on all the lword stuff 
which they had some nice symbols for prison furloughs and pledge 
of allegiance and aclu and stuff like that but it wasnt about 
those issues said wattenberg a democrat 
the reason they played was because they resonated in terms of 
20 years of democratic party history as too liberal he said 
its not a small issue it is haunting this party it is which 
direction the plurality party in america wants to take the 
country 
on the other hand the democrats wimp charge quickly lost its 
punch as bush emerged from the gop convention in new orleans as 
captain marvel said wattenberg 
phillips said by going hardline on the cultural and 
patriotic issues bush drove down the wimp factor bush put on 
a bit of a john wayne outfit 
bushs highest negative rating in polls remains the perception 
that he is too close to the wealthy and too far from the middle 
class but phillips said dukakis failed to come on hard and tough 
and use economic populism and nationalism to get the guys in the 
bar in the ethnic sections of cleveland or your dirt farmer in 
rural alabama angry at the republicans 
robinson said in a time of real prosperity questions of 
economic justice and hostility toward big business do not cut it 
with the american public 
as for such emotional issues as flag and country you cant 
pretend that something that is an issue is not an issue robinson 
said it hurts the democrats when they try to dismiss this in 
some way as bigotry or tasteless or unamerican 
it is an issue to americans whether you wear your flag on your 
sleeve or whether you wear it on the seat of your pants he said 
republicans are not only willing to wear their flag on their 
sleeves theyre willing to wear it on their foreheads the 
democrats are willing to move it off their keester but they still 
want to keep it half covered and americans dont like that 
