electionyear demands from voters to do something about drugs 
have driven the bill rudman said people want us to respond 
they want leadership from the congress 
also unfinished is a compromise tax bill but housesenate 
negotiations broke off in disagreement friday imperiling chances 
of reaching a plan both chambers can accept 
the measure includes a package of corrections to the landmark 
1986 tax law some new tax cuts along with other tax increases to 
offset the reductions and a taxpayer bill of rights for 
persons facing internal revenue service enforcement actions 
the house plan raises taxes between 7 billion and 75 billion 
over the next three years compared to the price tag of just under 
3 billion for the senate package 
senate negotiators proposed a compromise 3 billion package the 
house responded friday with a 45 billion counter the senate side 
turned that plan down and the talks stalled 
we have not selected the pallbearers yet said sen max 
baucus dmont head of the senate negotiating team he said the 
two sides would try to talk again monday 
also pending on the legislative agenda are a variety of other 
bills including one that would elevate the veterans administration 
to cabinetlevel status the house approved that bill oct 6 
supporters of the legislation say upgrading the agencys status 
will give the nations 27 million veterans direct access to the 
white house it would be the governments 14th cabinet department 
when the house meets tuesday one of its first votes will be on 
a bill requiring full disclosure of credit card information to 
consumers the senate which returns to work on monday passed the 
bill last week 
the proposal requires banks department stores and other firms 
which offer credit cards to tell consumers about annual fees 
interest rates late fees and other information only a few states 
now have laws requiring public disclosure of such information 
before consumers receive the cards 
another piece of unfinished business is legislation providing 
the firstever restrictions on lobbying by former members of 
congress a plan that is part of a general tightening of federal 
rules against influence peddling by top government officials 
differing versions of the legislation have passed each chamber 
and the discrepancies must be worked out before it can win final 
approval 
</TEXT>
