state department officials engaged in quiet 
discussions last week about a man who although unseen by the 
outside world for nine years is at the heart of a diplomatic 
debate over one of the worlds most unfortunate countries 
he is pol pot whose 3year rule in cambodia during the late 
1970s led to the slaughter of perhaps 2 million of his countrymen 
before he and his khmer rouge allies were driven out by vietnamese 
invaders 
david hawk an authority on the khmer rouge says pol pot is 
believed to be operating out of a small town in thailand near the 
cambodian border plotting a return to power once the vietnamese 
carry out their stated intention to withdraw from cambodia in 1990 
hawk has written on cambodia for freedom house a new yorkbased 
human rights group and formerly worked for amnesty international 
the reagan administration has been using diplomatic pressure to 
encourage the vietnamese to fulfill their promise to withdraw but 
is trying to find a way to prevent the marxist khmer rouge from 
retaking power once that happens 
this issue is a major concern of prowestern countries in 
southeast asia and was discussed this past week during a visits to 
washington by former cambodian head of state prince norodom 
sihanouk and officials from the chinese foreign ministry 
the dilemma facing the administration is that the khmer rouge 
with help from china is by far the strongest of the three rebel 
groups fighting the vietnamese occupation forces the united states 
is providing nonlethal equipment to the other two groups one led 
by sihanouk the second by former prime minister son sann 
