<TEXT>
an expected purge of the communist 
party leadership will at best be only a start in trying to ease 
yugoslavias worst crisis since world war ii 
the party central committee meets monday to argue and approve 
what are billed as the most sweeping personnel changes in more than 
four decades in power 
a politburo member said sunday that 14 of the 23 members of the 
ruling politburo may be removed at the meeting of the policymaking 
central committee 
four have announced their intention to resign and politburo 
member vasil tupurkovski told reporters 10 others may be replaced 
however radical the changes are at mondays meeting they will 
be only a stage in what one bestselling writer and dissident 
called the long agony of breaking with founding father josip 
tito 
tito dominated yugoslavia for 35 years ruling supreme until he 
died in may 1980 his portrait still hangs in almost every public 
room in the country and is carried fondly by some of the serbian 
nationalists who have staged mass rallies throughout southern and 
eastern yugoslavia in recent months 
their devotion to tito is in some ways ironic since they hope 
to restructure the ineffective political system tito bequeathed his 
nation their demand for greater serbian control over the serbian 
republics two autonomous provinces of vojvodina and kosovo 
prompted the current political crisis 
serbian communist party leader slobodan milosevic has skillfully 
exploited the mass rallies he has achieved national prominence on 
the wave of indignation serbs feel about the alleged harassment of 
their fellow christian slavs in kosovo the ancient serbian kingdom 
that is now dominated by ethnic albanians who are mainly moslem 
in exploiting the rallies milosevic has broken the order laid 
down by tito who gave broad autonomy to yugoslavias six republics 
and two provinces and annually rotated national offices among them 
to prevent one region from dominating the others 
milosevics drive has alarmed nonserbian communist leaders who 
fear the nations largest ethnic group wants greater control over 
yugoslav affairs 
yet they cannot ignore his popularity in serbia and the broader 
appeal of his calls for changes in the aging and sometimes 
ineffective ruling elite 
on television and in newspaper columns last week leaders 
engaged in an unprecedented public dispute over which leaders from 
which region will stand or fall when the central committee replaces 
up to onethird of its 165 members at mondays meeting 
in these circumstances it is easier to teach a whale to play 
the tambourine than to carry out the personnel changes commented 
the belgrade daily borba 
the ethnic arguments are only part of yugoslavias problem 
unwise borrowing in the 1970s and the lack of a strong federal 
government to manage the economy have led to economic crisis with 
the foreign debt at 21 billion and annual inflation at 217 percent 
living standards have fallen by onehalf since 1980 and 
austerity measures adopted in may have slashed salaries while 
prices continue to rise 
striking workers have taken to the streets in increasing 
numbers prompting the alarmed government to seek permission from 
the international monetary fund to relax the austerity program 
the ethnic and economic arguments sometimes obscure the growing 
calls to abandon oneparty rule and staterun economic management 
the corruption in each yugoslav republic angers the impoverished 
workers and the verbose and tangled communist jargon that 
surrounds most political pronouncements annoys even communists 
themselves 
after watching members of the national party politburo and the 
kosovo leadership debate for seven hours in kosovos capital 
pristina on tuesday the party leadership of the serbian town of 
titovo uzice commented if the debate at mondays meeting is 
dominated by the tenor of the one in pristina then it had 
better be canceled 
this frustration indicates the pressure for change in 
yugoslavia but writer dobrica cosic a wartime hero and former 
communist purged by tito in 1968 predicts that rearranging its 
political system will be a long agony for decades we have 
lived in a false situation cosic said in an interview false 
standards a false economy a false unity a false freedom at 
some moment the potentials of that fiction are exhausted and that 
moment is approaching 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
alison smale chief of the associated press 
bureau in vienna frequently covers yugoslavia and traveled to 
belgrade for this story 
