saudi arabian oil minister hisham 
nazer called for solidarity to bring us all good as he opened a 
meeting sunday with five other members of the gulf cooperation 
council 
the ministers statement carried by the official saudi press 
agency said that low oil prices brought on by overproduction 
require joint action to bring prosperity to our nation and 
countries 
the report did not outline what plan nazer might present during 
the meeting called to forge a joint strategy to help opec prop up 
deteriorating oil prices 
four of the six gcc members saudi arabia kuwait qatar and 
the united arab emirates are ranking members of the 13nation 
organization of petroleum exporting countries while gcc members 
oman and bahrain are not part of opec their economies depend on 
oil export revenues 
the meeting at gcc headquarters here began early sunday evening 
the ministers did not speak to reporters before the single session 
began 
a worldwide oil glut has sent crude prices tumbling as much as 
8 below the 18abarrel opec benchmark much of the excess crude 
comes from gulf producers including iraq and iran 
opec members collectively are pumping more than 3 million 
barrels in excess of the aggregate ceiling the cartel agreed to in 
late 1986 to try to defend the 18 price 
many producers have openly ignored their quotas the united arab 
emirates for example renounced its 948000barreladay quota and 
is pumping about 15 million barrels daily 
saudi arabia announced it will no longer cut production and 
sacrifice its revenue to defend prices it has exceeded its quota 
of 43 million barrels per day in recent weeks to pressure other 
overproducers into respecting the quota system 
industry executives and western diplomats believe that the gcc 
ministers have to discuss their own quotas and consider means of 
coercing iraq and iran into cooperating 
the two countries are emerging from an 8year war both have 
said they will pump as much oil as they deem necessary to finance 
billions of dollars in reconstruction 
iraq has suggested it will cooperate with opec irans 
parliamentary speaker hashemi rafsanjani said friday that there 
was no reason to quarrel with the countries on the southern coast 
of the gulf over the oil market 
if we quarrel the situation will remain as it is now why 
should oil sell at 10 or 11 
the saudi newspaper arab news noted that iraq and iran want 
really high revenue be it by pumping or through high prices by 
cooperating and cutting prooduction 
the paper said producers are considering raising the opec 
ceiling by raising members quotas but such an arrangement has to 
wait for the upcoming meeting of opecs strategy committee 
if all these efforts fail to stem the overproduction problem 
we are poised for another price crash a senior oil source told 
the paper 
